Topic Modeling: Katy Perry or Metallica?

Jamie Reilly, Ph.D.

October 27, 2020

Katy Perry vs.Metallica Lyrics

Read in the data

my_dir <- "/Volumes/GoogleDrive/My Drive/Reilly_RData/TM_TopicModelExerciseKatyPerry/lyrics/"
lyrics <- readtext(paste0(my_dir, "*.txt"))

Convert to corpus object

songs <- corpus(lyrics)

Add artist meta-data

Quanteda uses docvars to add user specified variables/annotation. In this case, we want to annotate the artist associated with each set of lyrics

metadoc(songs, "artist") <- c(rep("katy", 10), rep("metallica", 10))
summary(songs, showmeta = TRUE)

Corpus to document feature matrix (DFM)

Convert the corpus to a document term matrix well to be more precise, a document feature matrix because elements that are not words are also included

songsDFM <- dfm(songs, remove = stopwords(source = "smart"), remove_punct = TRUE, 
    tolower = TRUE)
print(songsDFM)  #prints all rows of the DFM and columns 1-15

Create dfm by artist

Group by a document variable - in this case we want to split a DFM by Katy Perry vs.Metallica

by_artist <- dfm(songs, groups = "_artist", remove = stopwords(source = "smart"), 
    remove_punct = TRUE, tolower = TRUE)
dfm_sort(by_artist)[, 1:25]

Simple topic modeling

song_topics <- dfm_trim(songsDFM, min_termfreq = 3, max_docfreq = 25)

dotchart((doc_similarity), pch = 12)

# hierarchical clustering - get distances on normalized dfm
tstat_dist <- textstat_dist(dfm_weight(songsDFM, scheme = "prop"))
# hiarchical clustering the distance object
songs_cluster <- hclust(as.dist(tstat_dist))
# label with document names
songs_cluster$labels <- docnames(songsDFM)
# plot as a dendrogram
plot(songs_cluster, xlab = "", sub = "", main = "Euclidean Distance on Normalized Token Frequency")
